Welcome, Cadet.
Before you can pilot a starship through the volatile asteroid fields of the stock market, you must first ensure your ship’s life support systems are fully operational. Investing while you are bleeding money or drowning in debt is like trying to jump to hyperspace with a cracked hull.

This level covers the fundamental physics of personal finance. Master these, and you will achieve financial escape velocity.

0.1 Power Generation (Income Dynamics)
To move your ship forward, you need to generate "Credits" (Money). There are three distinct types of engines you can use to generate this power:

Active Income (The Main Thrusters): This is the income you earn by directly trading your time and labor for credits. It includes your salary, hourly wages, or freelance work.

The Problem: If you stop working, the engine stops. You are physically limited by the 24 hours in a day. You can never get rich purely on active income because your time is finite.

Passive Income (Solar Panels): This is income generated automatically with little to no daily effort. Examples include rental income from property you own, royalties from a book you wrote, or selling digital software.

The Benefit: It generates credits even while you are in cryo-sleep.

Portfolio Income (Automated Mining Drones): This is money made from paper assets. It includes dividends (companies sharing profits with you), interest from bonds, or capital gains (buying a stock for ₹100 and selling it for ₹150).

🚀 The Ultimate Goal (Escape Velocity): Financial independence is purely mathematical. You reach it the exact moment your Passive Income + Portfolio Income becomes greater than your monthly living expenses. At that point, working becomes a choice, not a necessity.

0.2 Hull Breaches (Budgeting & Leakage)
A spaceship is a closed system. If your ship is leaking oxygen faster than it generates it, you will not survive. In finance, we manage this using the 50/30/20 Rule.

Every time credits enter your account, they must be strictly routed into three separate tanks:

50% for Needs (Life Support): These are non-negotiable survival expenses. Rent, groceries, electricity, medical insurance, and basic transportation. If your needs take up more than 50% of your income, your hull is too heavy—you must either increase your income or downgrade your lifestyle.

30% for Wants (The Holodeck): This is for your sanity and enjoyment. Dining out, video games, vacations, and premium subscriptions.

20% for Savings & Investing (Ship Upgrades): This money is untouchable. It is used exclusively to build your Emergency Shield (savings) and buy income-producing assets (investing).

⚠️ Beware of Cosmic Radiation (Inflation): Inflation is the invisible force that slowly decays the purchasing power of your credits. If you just hide your cash under a mattress, it loses roughly 5% to 6% of its value every single year. To fight inflation, your 20% savings must eventually be invested in assets that grow faster than the inflation rate.

0.3 The Flow Gauge (Balance Sheets & Cash Flow)
To be a successful commander, you must know how to read your ship's telemetry. This requires understanding the difference between an Asset and a Liability.

An Asset puts credits into your pocket, whether you work or not. (e.g., A dividend-paying stock, a fixed deposit, a rental property).

A Liability takes credits out of your pocket. (e.g., A car loan, a credit card bill, a subscription service).

The Trap: Most cadets buy liabilities (like an expensive iPhone on EMI) and mistakenly think they are assets. True wealth is built by using your active income to buy assets, which then buy your luxuries.

Calculating Net Worth: Your Net Worth is the ultimate score of your financial game.
Formula: Total Assets minus Total Liabilities = Net Worth.

0.4 Emergency Shields (The Safety Net)
Space is unpredictable. You could face a sudden engine failure (job loss), a meteor strike (medical emergency), or a system hack (unexpected major repair). Before you buy a single stock or crypto token, you MUST build your Emergency Shield.

The 6-Month Rule: You must calculate your bare minimum monthly survival cost (your "Needs" from the 50/30/20 rule). Multiply that number by 6. This is your target shield capacity.

Where to store it: This money must be highly liquid (instantly accessible). Do not put your emergency fund in the stock market—if the market crashes on the exact same day you lose your job, you are wiped out. Keep this money in a high-yield Savings Account or an easily breakable Fixed Deposit (FD).

Rule of Thumb: This money is not meant to make you rich. It is meant to protect the money that will make you rich.

0.5 Gravitational Drag (Debt Management)
Debt is a gravitational pull. Used correctly, it can slingshot you forward. Used poorly, it is a black hole that will crush your ship.

Bad Debt (The Black Hole): Borrowing money at high interest rates to buy depreciating liabilities. Credit card debt (often charging 30-40% interest annually) is a category-5 emergency. You must redirect all available power to pay this off immediately.

Good Debt (Gravity Assist): Borrowing money at low interest rates to buy assets that increase in value or generate income. For example, an education loan that drastically increases your future salary, or a business loan used to buy a machine that prints money.

Your CIBIL Score (Galactic Reputation): This is a 3-digit number (ranging from 300 to 900) that tells banks how trustworthy you are. Paying your credit card bills on time pushes this number up. A high score means banks will lend you money at cheaper interest rates in the future.

🏁 LEVEL 0 CLEARANCE CHECK
Are your life support systems stable? If your Emergency Shield is fully charged, and your Bad Debt is neutralized, you are cleared to proceed to the Shipyard.